"Kale G.R., Kulkarni B.D., Joshi A.R.","Thermodynamic study of combining chemical looping combustion and combined reforming of propane",2010,"Fuel","89","10",,"3141","3146",,,10.1016/j.fuel.2010.05.029,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77954802064&partnerID=40&md5=6856bc4deec3a81605be18920a008742","Chemical Engineering and Process Development Division, National Chemical Laboratory, Pune 411008, India","Kale, G.R., Chemical Engineering and Process Development Division, National Chemical Laboratory, Pune 411008, India; Kulkarni, B.D., Chemical Engineering and Process Development Division, National Chemical Laboratory, Pune 411008, India; Joshi, A.R., Chemical Engineering and Process Development Division, National Chemical Laboratory, Pune 411008, India","Existing energy generation technologies emit CO2 gas and are posing a serious problem of global warming and climate change. The thermodynamic feasibility of a new process scheme combining chemical looping combustion (CLC) and combined reforming (CR) of propane (LPG) is studied in this paper. The study of CLC of propane with CaSO4 as oxygen carrier shows thermodynamic feasibility in temperature range (400-782.95 °C) at 1 bar pressure. The CO2 generated in the CLC can be used for combined reforming of propane in an autothermal way within the temperature range (400-1000 °C) at 1 bar pressure to generate syngas of ratio 3.0 (above 600 °C) which is extremely desirable for petrochemical manufacture. The process scheme generates (a) huge thermal energy in CLC that can be used for various processes, (b) pure N2 and syngas rich streams can be used for petrochemical manufacture and (c) takes care of the expensive CO2 separation from flue gas stream and CO2 sequestration. The thermoneutral temperature (TNP) of 702.12 °C yielding maximum syngas of 5.98 mol per mole propane fed, of syngas ratio 1.73 with negligible methane and carbon formation was identified as the best condition for the CR reactor operation. The process can be used for different fuels and oxygen carriers. © 2009 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Chemical looping combustion; CLC; CO2 utilization; Energy generation","Auto-thermal; Carbon Formation; Chemical looping combustion; Energy generations; Existing energies; New process; Oxygen Carrier; Process schemes; Reforming of propane; Syn-gas; Temperature range; Thermodynamic feasibility; Thermodynamic studies; Flue gases; Fluidized bed combustion; Global warming; Methane; Oxygen; Petrochemicals; Propane; Thermodynamics; Temperature",,,,,,"Lyngfelt, A., Leckner, B., Mattisson, T., A fluidized-bed combustion process with inherent CO2 separation; Application of chemical-looping combustion (2001) Chem Eng Sci, 56 (10), pp. 3101-3113; Johansson, E., Mattisson, T., Lyngfelt, A., Thunman, H., A 300 W laboratory reactor system for chemical-looping combustion with particle circulation (2006) Fuel, 85 (1011), pp. 1428-1438; Abad, A., Mattisson, T., Lyngfelt, A., Rydén, M., Chemical-looping combustion in a 300 W continuously operating reactor system using a manganese-based oxygen carrier (2006) Fuel, 85 (9), pp. 1174-1185; Cho, P., Mattisson, T., Lyngfelt, A., Comparison of iron-, nickel-, copper- and manganese-based oxygen carriers for chemical-looping combustion (2004) Fuel, 83 (9), pp. 1215-1225; Adanez, J., De Diego, L.F., Garcia-Labiano, F., Gayán, P., Abad, A., Palacios, J.M., Selection of oxygen carriers for chemical-looping combustion (2004) Energ Fuel, 18 (2), pp. 371-377; Jin, H., Okamoto, T., Ishida, M., Development of a novel chemical-looping combustion: Synthesis of a solid looping material of NiO/NiAl2O4 (1999) Indus Eng Chem Res, 38 (1), pp. 126-132; Mattisson, T., Lyngfelt, A., Cho, P., The use of iron oxide as an oxygen carrier in chemical-looping combustion of methane with inherent separation of CO2 (2001) Fuel, 80 (13), pp. 1953-1962; Ishida, M., Jin, H., Okamoto, T., A fundamental study of a new kind of medium material for chemical-looping combusti